{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oedipusrex_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280607733/1957081801/0124.xml":{"full_text":"A-26\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, Washington, D. C.\nauNPAT, acopst is, iaay\nyours\nf\u00b0 r asking\nIf you\u2019d like a regular look at market condition!,\ntogether with our opinion of various securities,\njust phone or write us. You will receive our\nMarket Letter every other week it is yours\nwithout charge or obligation.\n\nWe will be open Saturday\u20149 AM. \u2019til l PM.\nAPR\nAUCHINCLOSS, PARKER A REDPATR\n729 Sired, N.t. NAtiunal 14)2:!\nMembers Am York Sleek Exchange end Other Leading Exchanges\nOffered \"j AUTO MATION\nfor the\nfirst time j.. SHARES, Inc.\n1 1\nAutomation Shares, Inc., is a professionally\nmanaged Mutual Fund seeking possible LONG\nTERM GROWTH of capital and income\nthrough a diversified investment program\nlargely in companies participating in the\nmanufacture, rental, installation or servicing\nof automation devices and equipment or the\ndesign and development of automation equip*\nment, processes or systems.\nFor your free copy of the facts about Auto\nmation Shares, Inc., please use coupon for\nprospectus.\nor phone CO. 5-4992\nThi Matthew Corporation\nInvestment Securities\n1524 Conn. Are. N.W.\nHaase send copy of AUTOMATION SHAMS, Inc*\nprospectus to\u2019\nNAME\nADDRESS\nTax-free yields hit 22-year high! j\n4.00% to 5.60%\nNow Available\nWith yields the highest in over 20 years,\nmany income-conscious individuals are invest\ning their funds in Municipal Bonds. Yields\nas high as 5.60% are now obtainable on some\nissues\u2014all of which is exempted by law from\nFederal Income Taxes.\nTo equal this tax-free return of 5.60%, a tax\nable security would have to yield 11.20% \u2014for\nan unmarried individual in a sl6-118.000 tax\nbracket filing a single return \u2014and of course\nmuch more in the higher brackets.\nMoreover, current high yields are no reflec\ntion on the quality of the bonds, but a direct\nresult of tight money. Traditionally, Munici\npals are the safest investment next to U. S.\nGovernment Obligations,\nTo assist investors seeking income opportu\nnities, we have prepared a list of selected\ntax-exempt issues which is available without\nobligation.\nA Booklet \u201cHow to frefit Through Tax-txemption\"\u2014which\ndescribes Municipal\u25a0 Bonds\u2014will also be included.\nOpen Evenings Until 9 PM.\u2014Saturdays Until 2 PM.\nMembers New York Stock Exchange and Other Leading Exchanges\nSTRUT FLOOR. CAFRITZ BUILDING\nWASHINGTON IETHESDA ALEXANDRIA\nCofritz luilding Maryland Virginia\n1625 Eys St. N.W. 7730 Wisconsin Art. Georgs Mason Hotel\nDl. 7-5700 OL. 4-3000 Kl. 1-5700\nIJH HUH.\nnot |HSt office furniture\nIt's old-fashioned just to buy office furniture. The wise\nbusinessman calls on his qualified office furniture dealer's\nbroad background and knowledge of office planning for\nmore efficient office operation. Today's exciting designs in\noffice furniture fit into such a plan, but the planning must\ncome first.\nI #(rrfifiri\\\nwin I IWe will be gled to discuss your office pfenning\nproblems with you at no cost.\nno obligation\u2014just call\u2014NA. 8-4181\nCHAS. G. STOTT CO.\nOffice Planning anJ \u00dcbecoraHng Specialists\nFurniture Showroomst\nI*lo New York Ave., N.W., Washington, D. C\n\u202240* Oeorgia Ave., Silver Spring, Md.\n|t\u2018 __\n\u25a0fiyvy^TfWTnrvV\u00dfTSTSTn^niTTlVTVnSnffH\nWmJXMMUdJBJAMJJJMALXXA&mjyjLAZVLMLdUmMuIMMJKi\n\nHot Shoppes Volume\nSoars 23.3 Pet. in Year\nBy DONALD B. HADLEY\nSales of Hot Shoppes, Inc., soared to a new all-time record\nof $35,961,000 in the fiscal year ended July 38, President J.\nWillard Marriott announced yesterday.\nThe new peak was up 33.3 per cent from $39,171,000 In the\nprevious year and Mr. Marriott pointed out that the full impact\nfrom recent additions to the restaurant chain was not reflected\nIn the increase.\nMr. Marriott gave no Indica\ntion of the profits outlook tof\nthe year pending completion\nof the annual report and an In\ndependent audit. He said the\nchain had 73 units in operations\nat the end of the year, com\npared with 64 a year earlier.\nHe also announced plans for\nopening of two \u201cMighty Mo\u201d\ncurb service restaurants in\nWashington suburbs with a\nlimited and specialty menu. Lo\ncations were not given, but one\nwill be opened in September\nand the other later in' the fall.\nImproved Earnings Hinted,\nDespite Expansion Costs\nFor Investors the 164 ques\ntion la how much of the big\nsales Increase came through to\nprofits. There was some hint\nthat earnings also may show a\nsubstantial improvement al\nthough nonrecurring expenses\nof the company expansion\nprogram continue.\nIn the preceding fiscal year\nsales jumped 24 per cent while\nprofits of 3847.987 or $1.09 a\nshare, after taxes, showed\nhardly any change from $835,-\n303 or 31.08 In the previous\nperiod. Heavy expansion costs\nwere cited as the reason.\nThe company\u2019s final two res\ntaurants on the New York\nThruway have opened, making\na total of seven. Three units\nnow are in operation on the\nSunshine Parkway in Florida.\nThe Marriott Motor Hotel\nand restaurant were opened in\nJanuary as well as drlve-in\nrestaurants In Greensboro, N.\nC., and in Wheaton, Md. A\ncafeteria in The Hecht Co.\nstore in Edmonston Village.\nBaltimore, inflight feeding\nservice In Dalits. Texas, and\nemploye restaurants In several\nIndustrial plants also were\nadded.\ns2s Million Bond Offering\nApproved by VEPCO Board\nDirectors of Virginia Electric\nand Power Co. have approved\nplans for offering S2O million\nof first-mortgage bonds in De\ncember to complete financing\nof the company\u2019s 1957 con\nstruction program costing\naround S7O million.\nThe new Issue will be sold\nat competitive bidding and bids\nare scheduled for opening on\nDecember 3, President Erwin\nH. Will announced.\nDirectors approved plans for\nVEPCO\u2019s participation In the\nproposed construction of an\natomic reactor by Carolines\nI Virginia Nuclear Power Asso\nciate*. They declared the usual\nquarterly dividends on common\nand preferred stocks, payable\nSeptember 20 to holders of rec\nord August 30.\nThe company\u2019s net Income in\nJuly was $2,123,000 or 13.3\ncento a share vs. $1,807,000 or\n11.0 cento in July last year. Net\nfor 12 months ended July 31\nwas $22,768,000 or $1.41 a share\nvs. $20,374,000 or *1.35 In the\npreceding period.\nL. H. Carr firm Acquires\nScatter Communications\nScatter Communications. Inc.,\nof Bethesda. Md.. has been\nacquired by L. H. Carr dt Asso\nciates of Washington. It was\nannounced.\nThe firm waa organized\nearlier this year by a team of\nexecutives, engineers and sup\nport personnel, who engineered\nand supervised Installation of\nthe Air Force's North Atlantic\nScatter Circuit.\nLester H. Carr Is owner and\npresident of L. H. Carr Bt Asso\nciates. He Is president and\nan owner of Development En\ngineering Corp. of Leesburg,\nVa., and has an interest In\nContinental Electronics of Dal\nlas, Tex. He will be chairman\nof the Bcatter firm.\nHarry M. Tayloe, owner of\nH. M. Tayloe dc Associates, is\npresident of Scatter and Clifton\nP. Foss Is executive vice presi\ndent. William E. Yost, Jr., Is\nOffered for the\nfirst time\nAUTOMATION\nr SHARES, Inc.\nAntomilion Share*, Inr\u201e ii\nprofenionilfe managed Mu\ntual Fund iceking poaaible\nLONG TERM GROWTH ol\ncapital and income through\na diversified invealment pro\ngram largely in companies\nparticipating in the manu\nfacture, rental, installation\nor aerviring of automation\ndevice! and equipment or\nthe deaign and development\ni of antomatiun equipment,\nproceaaea or ayatema.\nI\nFor your free ropy of the\nfacta about Automation\nSharea, Inc., aimply phone or\nmail coupon below.\n\n'i-\u2014--\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nFERRIS CO;\nMembers N Y. Stock Sic hence\nBSS WASHINGTON BUILDINQ\nl.Vth and N. Y. Ave.. ST 8-6024\nPlease send me an\nI AUTOMATION SHARES\nprospactus\nNAM!\nI ADD6I66\nDR. SUMNER SLICHTER\nvice president, engineering, and\nP. L. McCutchen la project\nmanager.\nSllchter Wifi Answer\nQuestions at Forum\nFinancial and business execu\ntives, economists and commer\ncial and financial advisers of a\nnumber of foreign governments\nhave been invited to a business\noutlook forum arranged by\nStandard Bt Poor's Corp. at the\nShoreham Hotel on Tuesday,\nSeptember 24.\nDr. Sumner Sllchter, Harvard\nprofessor of economics and con\nsulting economist for Standard\nBt Poor\u2019s, will answer a series of\nquestions from members of the\nfirm\u2019s economics staff.\nD. C. Insurance Leaden\nOn Convention Program\nDistrict life insurance execu\ntives will participate In the pro\ngram of the 68th annual con\nvention of the National Associa\ntion of Life Underwriters at\nDetroit September 15-20.\nJ. Hicks Baldwin, general\nagent for New England Life, is\ntreasurer of NALU and Louis J.\nGrayson of Travelers Is an as\nsociation trustee and chairman I\nof its committee on veterans 1\naffairs.\nC. Carney Smith, general\nagent for Mutual Benefit Life,\nwill moderate a panel of gen\neral agents and managers. He\nalso Is chairman of the commit\ntee on relations with national\nsecurities dealers.\nThelma Davenport, special\nagent for Northwestern Mutual,\nla chairman of the NALU's com\nmittee of women underwriters\nand also heads the education\ncommittee of the Women\u2019s\nQuarter Million Dollar Round\nTable.\nA large delegation from\nNALU headquarters here will\nbe headed by Lester O. Schri\nver, managing director.\nCost Accountants Plan\nForum Discussions\nPanels of experts from vari\nous industries and the Govern\nment will discuss cost control\nat the plant level In a aeries of\nWednesday night forum meet\nings planned by Washington\nChapter. National Association\nof Cost Accountants.\nSUrting October 2, the meet\nings will be from 8 to 8 pm. at\nthe Chesapeake Bt Potomac Tel\nephone Co. conference room.\n930 H street N.W. Each panel\nwill Include a chairman, busi\nnessman and Government offi\ncial. Chairman and dates fol\nlow:\nElmer E. Chenowith, October\n6: Martin E. Finney, October 9;\nHarney A. Brasfleld, October\n23; John E. Carroll, November\n6: Martin E. Pinner. November\n13, and Mr. Brasfleld, Decem\nber 4.\nRichmond Reserve Banks\nPoints to Uncertainty\nRecord-smashing demands for\nfunds continued to push capi\ntal market rates to new highs\nthrough the first half of this\nyear, the Federal Reserve Bank\nof Richmond commented In its\nmonthly review yesterday.\nThe bank noted that \u201cUn\ncertainty appears to have\nbeen exerting greater influence\nIn the flrat half of 1957 than\nduring the growing tightness in\n1956. A feeling that our high\nriding economy, afflicted with\nmultipronged price pressures\n(Increased money costs. In\ncreased labor costs, and in\ncreased prices of commodities\nand services) must eventually\nrein In, has cast a sombre hue\nover the financial markets.\n\u201cYet. despite the expecUtlon\nthat a change was due or over\ndue. no weakening In the de\nmands on the capiUl markets\nfor funds has materialized, the\narticle said.\nTom Kaufman Joins\nCapiUl Aid Agency\nHenry J. Kaufman and Asso\nciates, Washington advertising\nand public relations firm, an\nnounced the addition of Tom\nKaufman to 1U public rela\ntions division\nA native of Milwaukee, Wls.,\nMr. Kaufman operated his own 1\npublic relations offlee there and\npreviously waa a public rela\ntions specialist with Allls-\nChalmers.\nIn Milwaukee, Mr. Kaufman,\n32, was a director of the Mil\nwaukee Junior Chamber of\nCommerce and a deputy gov\nernor of Toastmasters Interna\ntional. He graduated from the\nUniversity of Wisconsin In\n1949.\nGiant Food Stores Plans\n1 New Store In Hampton\nOiant Pood Stores of Wash\nington announced plans for a\n32.000-square-foot food market\nIn the Southland Shopping\nCenter to be built at Hamp\nton, Va.\nScheduled to open In the fall\nI of 1959, the new center will\nI serve Norfolk, Hampton and\nI Newport News.\nNEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE WEEKLY SUMMARY\nWEEK ENDING SATURDAY, AUGUST 17. 1957\n*sFLem HFtSs ifflw Bt*k Low Ones Si.\nA\n*l* 37% Abbott Ll b SO 46% 44% 44*-!*\nUMvs \u00bba Abbott Lett is ioi 999* 9*%-i%\n17% 15'* h\u00bbC Vood as 34 15V* 14% ISU+ V*\n649 b 50v* ACT lad 4 36 01 59% 95'4-lV*\nJ 6% 13Vi ACTWrt* Ob 55 14% UM. I)9*-1\n3\u00bb* 30V* Aemo Stool 3 45 31 SOV* 31V*- V*\nS7V* IJt* AdamaEx Ms ST SS 156% 259*- V*\nI*9* MS Admiral 54 10V* 59* 599- 9*\nSOV* Aoroqoib Mb x 35 S 5 17V* 1799-1\n31V* lev* ActnaSdlVVb 11 SON SOV* 169*4 V*\nSs9* 46% Air Ra6ac 2H alls 55 519* 53%-lV*\n*V* AlaakaJuntaa SS 3V* 5 J%+ V*\n159* 15V* Moo Prod 1 *4 16V* 15V* 15**- V*\n\u2022V* 59* AflMbolw 777 09* 89* 89*+ 9*\nOH 469* AlleaLod.su t ISS SOV* 489* 46%- V*\nI\u00bbV* 13 Allooladl 17 10V* 159* 159*+ 9*\n\u2022m* 85 AtHodCbm 1b x 135 879* 85 8595-19*\nS3V* SlV* AfflodKidl.SOax 14 85V* Sl9* 119*+ 9*\n309* 17V* ADM Mill* 1 31 ISV* 17V* 17V4-IV*\n*4V* 15V* AIIM Pd I.M 13 119* 11V* !IV*+l\n479* 40V* MHodStorotl SO 45 4S9* 449 V*\n36V* 3t Mila Chaim 1 I*4 339 b 33V* 33V*- 9b\n3J 349* UMtPCim 3* 359* 349* 35**\u2014 9*\n\u2022S'* 019 b Alum Ltd 00 475 44V* 419* 46 -IV*\nio* ao aiooo 1.10 xisf as ais* asvs-m\n*3V* 41 Amoraec *4d M 40V* 43V* 439*-3\n147V* 104V* Amerada 1 I*l 119V* 1189* 11IV*-2V*\n309* dOV* AmAsCbm la 37 7094 *B9* 70*4+1**\n14V* 17V* Am Allt 1 *lB5 18V* 17V* la V*\n37V* 319* Am\u00dfakrr l.Wx 11 309 b 35V* 309*+ V*\n31 I*9* Am\u00dfkNtel M 10 17 ISV* I*9*- V*\n17 159* Am Booeb lb 137 109 b 159 b SO**- V*\n37V* 419* Am\u00df\u00dfba*S.4oi 143 31 SOV* 319*- 9*\n140 1049* Am Br Shaft IS 1189* 126V* IST -1\n149 k 189* Am\u00dfrdPar la 114 159* 1*9% 1894-1\n\u00ab9* 49* AooCbiaiUSS 30 39* 5V* SV*\n459* 359 b Am Cab 1 S3B 439 b 419* 43 -IV*\n41V* 359* A mean of I*4 5* 379* 37V* 37V*+ V*\n*4V* 489* Am Chain IV* 18 55 539* 31V4-IV*\n\u00bb3V* 33V* Am CMcte S 30 S5V* 50 50v*+l>*\n319* 17 Am Coiortx 1 13 30 S39h 30 +V*\n40'* 4194 AmCranamM 366 43>4 41 43